Amendment No. 3 to SB2634
Roberts
Signature of Sponsor
AMEND S e n ate Bill No. 2634 House Bill No. 2167*
by deleting all language after the caption and substituting:
WHEREAS, Tennessee is known as the Volunteer State in part due to its proud tradition
of civic participation, community service, and volunteerism that reflects the values of its people;
and
WHEREAS, Colby's Law is intended to further our State's proud history for generations
to come by ensuring that all public institutions of higher learning across the State create
meaningful opportunities for their students to embrace their duty of civic engagement through
participation in the electoral process; and
WHEREAS, removing academic barriers to student participation in a regular November
election day event has proven to increase student voter turnout and volunteerism in elections
and campaign activities; and
WHEREAS, Colby's Law is also consistent with the value that academia places on
volunteerism in that encouraging students to engage in their communities through dedicated
student service hours on a regular November election day would be beneficial to both the
student and the community; now, therefore,
BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE:
SECTION 1. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 2, Chapter 1, is amended by adding the
following as a new section:
(a) This section is known and may be cited as "Colby's Law."
(b) Each public institution of higher education shall, in the week immediately
preceding, and on the date of, a regular November election, implement reasonable
SA1059
018119
- 1 -

measures to promote civic engagement and facilitate student participation in the election
process, such as providing information about voting locations, encouraging community
volunteerism and service for civic engagement, and removing unnecessary barriers for
student participation in the electoral process.
(c) An institution may observe an academic holiday on the date of a regular
November election. An institution that elects to observe an academic holiday on the
date of a regular November election is not required to close the institution or to suspend
its operations, including, but not limited to, clinical programs, research activities,
internships, practicums, professional programs, online education, student services,
health services, public safety operations, or any other essential institutional function.
(d) As used in this section, "academic holiday" means a day on which a public
institution of higher education has elected to suspend or modify regularly scheduled in-
person instructional activities, as determined by the institution.
SECTION 2. This act takes effect upon becoming a law, the public welfare requiring it.
